TELUS Corporation

8-555 Robson Street 
Vancouver BC V6B 3K9 Canada
Phone: +1 604-___-____
Fax: +1 604-___-____
http://www.telus.com





1034
Managers




2265
IT employees




$452.7MEST.
IT Budget




TELUS Corporation is a national telecommunications company in Canada, offering a range of wireline and wireless communications products and services including data, voice and entertainment. The company also operates several commercial data centers. TELUS Communications offers wireline services for TV,… MoreTELUS Corporation is a national telecommunications company in Canada, offering a range of wireline and wireless communications products and services including data, voice and entertainment. The company also operates several commercial data centers. TELUS Communications offers wireline services for TV, phone, and internet to business and consumer markets while TELUS Mobility offers wireless phone services. TELUS Business Solutions and TELUS Health provide managed information services and solutions to clients in enterprise markets and the health industry. The Business Solutions and the Health group were developed through the acquisition of Emergis, an eBusiness service provider, which was purchased by TELUS in 2008. TELUS Health has seen further expansion with the acquisitions of Wolf Medical Systems and KinLogix, both cloud-based health technology service providers, which were acquired in 2012.
The IT department for TELUS Corporation is dispersed across several locations in Canada. Core department leadership is located at the company’s headquarters in Burnaby, BC. A location in Longueuil, QC, serves as the headquarters for TELUS Health. TELUS Mobility staff… MoreThe IT department for TELUS Corporation is dispersed across several locations in Canada. Core department leadership is located at the company’s headquarters in Burnaby, BC. A location in Longueuil, QC, serves as the headquarters for TELUS Health. TELUS Mobility staff members are mainly located in Scarborough, ON. Other smaller sites support specialized or regional operations and house fewer technical assets.

 TELUS’ IT staff members are divided between internal operations and client-facing functions. Leaders working in technology strategy oversee the resources and staff that manage the various client-facing technology operations. Staff working in this area primarily have responsibilities in business intelligence and service delivery. Internally the company has staff dedicated to maintaining networks and infrastructure, business support operations, data centers, and information security. TELUS has embraced cloud technologies throughout its corporate operations.

 In 2010 the company began to host some of its application platforms online. Since then the company has continued to use the cloud to meet storage demands and support large databases for big data initiatives. In 2011 TELUS began work on a new data center to support cloud operations internally as well as provide cloud services to consumers. The company cloud strategy was further supported by the acquisitions of Wolf Medical Systems and KinLogix.  These acquisitions support TELUS Health’s push into cloud-based medical record services. The IT budget is typically finalized in Q3.

IT Intelligence Snippets

2013:
•>5 pb data volume company-wide across >10 data centers, and expects an annual data growth of 20-50%. 
•25-49% of its servers are to be virtualized by the end of 2013. 
•Corporate IT manages 30000 mobile devices, while 10000 are managed elsewhere. 
•Corporate IT manages 40000 desktops.
•Cost is the primary consideration for buying hardware, and it's standardized on 1-2 product vendors. 
•Data center strategy is centered on virtualizing x86 servers for most applications; standalone servers or mainframes for business critical applications, standardizing on unified server, storage, and network stacks, and minimizing cost.
•Long term plan for running new applications is to add servers and virtualize, but no new facilities are scheduled.





